I had also to get the geolocalization data for each neighborhood, because Foursquare require them.

So I used the geopy library.


```python
#!pip install geopy
from geopy import Nominatim
from geopy.exc import GeocoderUnavailable, GeocoderTimedOut, GeocoderServiceError

geolocator = Nominatim(user_agent="ny_explorer")

def geolocator_belohorizonte(neighborhood):    
    try:
        locator = geolocator.geocode(neighborhood +', Belo Horizonte')
    except (GeocoderUnavailable, GeocoderTimedOut, GeocoderServiceError):
        print('Geocoder unavailable or timed out... will try again!')
        locator = geolocator_belohorizonte(neighborhood)
    return locator

locators = bairros['Neighborhood'].apply(geolocator_belohorizonte)

bairros['Latitude'] = locators.apply(lambda v: v.latitude if v is not None else None)
bairros['Longitude'] = locators.apply(lambda v: v.longitude if v is not None else None)

bairros.dropna(inplace=True)

print(bairros.shape)
bairros.head()
```

```python
!conda install -c conda-forge folium=0.5.0 --yes # uncomment if needed
import folium # map rendering library

ilat = -19.9227318
ilon = -43.9450948

# create map of Belo Horizonte using latitude and longitude values
map_bh = folium.Map(location=[ilat,  ilon], zoom_start=10)

# add markers to map
for lat, lng, neighborhood in zip(bairros['Latitude'], bairros['Longitude'], bairros['Neighborhood']):
    label = '{}: ({}, {})'.format(neighborhood, lat, lng)
    label = folium.Popup(label, parse_html=True)
    folium.CircleMarker(
        [lat, lng],
        radius=5,
        popup=label,
        color='blue',
        fill=True,
        fill_color='#3186cc',
        fill_opacity=0.7,
        parse_html=False).add_to(map_bh)  

map_bh
```

Unfortunately, geopy was not accurate on many neighborhoods far from Belo Horizonte downtown.

So, let us restrict the analysis to neighborhoods not far from downtown.

Also, the location of Pindorama neighborhood is remarkably wrong. Let us just remove it from dataset.


```python
df = bairros[(bairros['Latitude']<ilat+0.09) & (bairros['Latitude']>ilat-0.09) & (bairros['Longitude']>ilon-0.06) & (bairros['Longitude']<ilon+0.06)]
df = df[df['Neighborhood'] != 'PINDORAMA']
```

Let's visualize the resulting dataset, now with social classes distinctions.


```python
import matplotlib.cm as cm
import matplotlib.colors as colors

classes = {'low':0, 'regular':1, 'high':2, 'luxury':3}

# create map
map_classes = folium.Map(location=[ilat,  ilon], zoom_start=11)

# set color scheme for the clusters
x = np.arange(4)
ys = [i + x + (i*x)**2 for i in range(4)]
colors_array = cm.rainbow(np.linspace(0, 1, len(ys)))
rainbow = [colors.rgb2hex(i) for i in colors_array]

# add markers to the map
markers_colors = []
for lat, lon, poi, socialclass in zip(df['Latitude'], df['Longitude'], df['Neighborhood'], df['Class']):
    label = folium.Popup(str(poi) + ' Class ' + socialclass, parse_html=True)
    folium.CircleMarker(
        [lat, lon],
        radius=5,
        popup=label,
        color=rainbow[classes[socialclass]-1],
        fill=True,
        fill_color=rainbow[classes[socialclass]-1],
        fill_opacity=0.7).add_to(map_classes)
    
map_classes
```
